## Configure Nginx as a reverse proxy for Node.js / Next.js on a VPS

### 1. Pre-flight checks
- Confirm you have SSH access to a VPS running Ubuntu 20.04+ or Debian 11+.
- Confirm you have a domain name pointing to the VPS IP (A record set, propagated).
- Confirm the Node.js/Next.js app runs and is accessible on a local port (e.g., 3000) on the VPS.
- Note the app port: this is what Nginx will proxy to. Replace `3000` in this guide with your actual port.

### 2. Install Nginx
```bash
sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade -y
sudo apt install nginx -y
sudo systemctl enable nginx
sudo systemctl start nginx
```
- Verify: `curl http://localhost` should return the Nginx welcome page.
- Open firewall ports: `sudo ufw allow 'Nginx Full'` (allows ports 80 and 443).

### 3. Install Node.js (if not already installed)
- Use NodeSource for a recent LTS version:
```bash
curl -fsSL https://deb.nodesource.com/setup_20.x | sudo -E bash -
sudo apt install nodejs -y
node --version  # should print v20.x
```

### 4. Install PM2 for process management
```bash
npm install -g pm2
```
- Start your app with PM2:
```bash
cd /var/www/your-app
pm2 start npm --name "your-app" -- start
pm2 startup  # follow the printed command to enable auto-start on reboot
pm2 save
```
- For Next.js: `pm2 start npm --name "nextjs" -- start`
- For a custom server: `pm2 start server.js --name "app"`
- Verify: `pm2 status` — the app should show `online`.

### 5. Create Nginx server block
- Create the config file:
```bash
sudo nano /etc/nginx/sites-available/your-app
```
- Paste the following (replace `your-domain.com` and `3000`):
```nginx
server {
    listen 80;
    server_name your-domain.com www.your-domain.com;

    location / {
        proxy_pass http://localhost:3000;
        proxy_http_version 1.1;
        proxy_set_header Upgrade $http_upgrade;
        proxy_set_header Connection 'upgrade';
        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme;
        proxy_cache_bypass $http_upgrade;
        proxy_read_timeout 86400;
    }

    # Serve Next.js static assets directly (skip Node.js for speed)
    location /_next/static {
        alias /var/www/your-app/.next/static;
        expires 1y;
        add_header Cache-Control "public, immutable";
    }
}
```
- The `Upgrade` / `Connection` headers are required for WebSocket support (e.g., HMR in dev, Socket.io in prod).

### 6. Enable the site and test config
```bash
# Enable the site
sudo ln -s /etc/nginx/sites-available/your-app /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/

# Remove the default site if it conflicts
sudo rm /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/default

# Test the config
sudo nginx -t

# Reload Nginx
sudo systemctl reload nginx
```
- `sudo nginx -t` MUST pass before reloading. If it shows errors, fix them first.

### 7. Install SSL with Let's Encrypt (Certbot)
```bash
sudo apt install certbot python3-certbot-nginx -y
sudo certbot --nginx -d your-domain.com -d www.your-domain.com
```
- Follow the prompts: enter your email, agree to TOS, choose to redirect HTTP to HTTPS (option 2).
- Certbot automatically modifies your Nginx config to add SSL and redirect HTTP → HTTPS.
- Verify auto-renewal: `sudo certbot renew --dry-run`

### 8. Final Nginx config (after Certbot — for reference)
- Certbot will produce something like:
```nginx
server {
    server_name your-domain.com www.your-domain.com;

    location / {
        proxy_pass http://localhost:3000;
        proxy_http_version 1.1;
        proxy_set_header Upgrade $http_upgrade;
        proxy_set_header Connection 'upgrade';
        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme;
        proxy_cache_bypass $http_upgrade;
    }

    listen 443 ssl;
    ssl_certificate /etc/letsencrypt/live/your-domain.com/fullchain.pem;
    ssl_certificate_key /etc/letsencrypt/live/your-domain.com/privkey.pem;
    include /etc/letsencrypt/options-ssl-nginx.conf;
    ssl_dhparam /etc/letsencrypt/ssl-dhparams.pem;
}

server {
    listen 80;
    server_name your-domain.com www.your-domain.com;
    return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
}
```

### 9. Set up gzip compression (optional but recommended)
- Edit `/etc/nginx/nginx.conf` and ensure inside the `http {}` block:
```nginx
gzip on;
gzip_types text/plain text/css application/json application/javascript text/xml application/xml;
gzip_comp_level 6;
gzip_min_length 1000;
```
- Then `sudo systemctl reload nginx`.

### 10. Deploy updates
```bash
# Pull latest code
cd /var/www/your-app && git pull

# Install dependencies and rebuild
npm ci && npm run build

# Reload app with PM2 (zero-downtime)
pm2 reload your-app
```
- `pm2 reload` performs a graceful reload with zero downtime. Use it for production updates.
- `pm2 restart` is a hard restart (brief downtime). Use only if reload fails.

### 11. Verify the setup
- Visit `https://your-domain.com` in a browser.
- The browser should show a valid padlock (SSL).
- HTTP requests to `http://your-domain.com` should automatically redirect to HTTPS.
- Run `pm2 status` to confirm the app is `online`.
- Run `sudo systemctl status nginx` to confirm Nginx is `active (running)`.

### Common errors & fixes
- **502 Bad Gateway** — Nginx is running but the Node.js app is not. Run `pm2 status` and `pm2 logs your-app` to diagnose.
- **`nginx -t` fails: `bind() to 0.0.0.0:80 failed`** — Port 80 is already in use. Find the process: `sudo lsof -i :80` and stop it.
- **SSL cert not found by Certbot** — The DNS A record for your domain hasn't propagated yet. Wait and retry: `dig your-domain.com` should return your VPS IP.
- **`104: Connection reset by peer`** — The app crashed. Check `pm2 logs your-app` for the error.
- **Cert renewal fails** — Port 80 must be open for the ACME challenge. Ensure `ufw allow 80` and no other service blocks it during renewal.
- **WebSocket (Socket.io) disconnects through Nginx** — Missing `Upgrade` and `Connection` headers. Add them to the location block (see step 5).
- **Static files served slow** — Remove the `/_next/static` alias if the path is wrong, or let Node.js serve them (remove the alias entirely) for simplicity.
- **`EACCES: permission denied` on port 80** — Node.js cannot bind to ports below 1024. Always run Node.js on port 3000+ and let Nginx proxy from 80.

### What NOT to do
- Do NOT run the Node.js app directly on port 80 — use Nginx as the entry point and keep Node.js on a high port (3000+).
- Do NOT skip `sudo nginx -t` before reloading — a config error will take down the entire Nginx server.
- Do NOT expose your app port (3000) directly in the firewall (`ufw`). Only ports 80 and 443 should be public.
- Do NOT use `pm2 restart` for production updates — use `pm2 reload` for zero-downtime graceful restart.
- Do NOT hardcode the Let's Encrypt cert path — Certbot manages it. If you renew or revoke, the path may change; always let Certbot update the Nginx config.
- Do NOT use the `default` Nginx site alongside your custom config — delete it from `sites-enabled` to avoid conflicts.
- Do NOT ignore SSL renewal expiry — set up a cron job or use `sudo crontab -e` to schedule `certbot renew --quiet` twice daily (Certbot's recommendation).
